Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Observations:¶

  • cost_of_the_order - The majority of orders cost between $10 and $25, indicating a right-skewed distribution. The average oreder cost is $16.5, with a $35 maximum.

  • rating - Following the conversion of 'Not given' to NaN, 736 ratings were missing, leaving 1162 valid ratings. Given that the distribution is left-skewed, the majority of consumers gave high ratings of 4 or 5. With a mean rating of 4.34 and 50% of evaluations of 5.0, overall customer satisfaction is demonstrated.

  • food_preparation_time - With an average of 27 minutes, the majority of meals is made between 23 to 31 minutes. The spread is moderate and the distribution is quite symmetrical. Consistent kitchen operations are indicated by the absence of significant outliers.

  • delivery_time - The average delivery time is around 24.16 minutes, with a range of 15 to 33 minutes. The majority of deliveries are finished in 20 to 28 minutes, with a little left skew. Boxplot supports a steady delivery process because there are no outliers.

  • restaurant_name/top_10_restaurants - With 219 orders, Shake Shack is the most popular restaurant. Blue Ribbon Sushi and The Meatball Shop come second with 119 and 132 orders, respectively. There is also a strong demand for restaurants like Parm, Parm House, and Num Pang Sandwich Shop. All top 10 restaurants received 70 or more orders, indicating they have a strong customer base. This indicates that certain restaurants are highly favored, perhaps due to their familiarity, cuisine appeal, or quality of service. The remaining 170 restaurants receive much fewer orders, indicating that a small number of locations account for the majority of business.

  • cuisine_type - The most popular cuisine is American with 584 orders, followed by Japanese, Italian, and Chinese with 470, 298, 215 orders respectively. French, Thai, Vietnamese, and Indian cuisines are less well-liked which shows a certain taste for East Asian and Western foods.

  • day_of_the_week - Weekends see the most orders (1351), while weekdays see the fewest (547). This suggests that demand is higher on weekends, most likely as a result of leisure time and the habit of eating out.

# 1. Corelation between Numerical Variables

df['rating'] = df['rating'].replace('Not given', np.nan).astype(float)

                             'food_preparation_time', 'delivery_time'])

            'food_preparation_time', 'delivery_time']

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

                    color='lightgreen', palette= 'Set1')

        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [ ]:
# Write the code here
def calculate_revenue(price):
    if price > 20:
        return price * 0.25
    elif price > 5:
        return price * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

df['revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_revenue)
net_revenue = df['revenue'].sum()
print(f"Net revenue is ${net_revenue:.2f}")

Net revenue is $1824.10

Observations: The company's total net revenue from all sales was $1824.10, of which 25% came from commissions on purchases above $20 and 15% from orders over $5. Most orders tend to be low-cost, resulting in a moderate overall income. Increasing high-value orders may enhance the company's profitability.¶

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]¶

In [ ]:
# Write the code here

df['delivery_time'] = df['delivery_time'].replace('Not given', np.nan).astype(float)
df['food_preparation_time'] = df['food_preparation_time'].replace('Not given', np.nan).astype(float)

df = df.dropna(subset=['delivery_time', 'food_preparation_time'])

df['total_time'] = df['delivery_time'] + df['food_preparation_time']
percentage = (df['total_time'] > 60).mean() * 100

print(f"{percentage:.2f}% of orders took more than 60 minutes.")

df.drop('total_time', axis=1, inplace=True)

11.31% of orders took more than 60 minutes.

Observations: Approximately 11.31% of all orders took longer than an hour to process and deliver. This suggests that even if most orders are completed in an hour, plenty of them still require longer, whether as a result of complicated food products, long wait periods, or delivery distance.¶

Question 16: The company wants to analyze the delivery time of the orders on weekdays and weekends. How does the mean delivery time vary during weekdays and weekends? [2 marks]¶

In [ ]:
# Write the code here

weekday_delivery_times = df[df['day_of_the_week'] != 'Weekend']['delivery_time']
weekend_delivery_times = df[df['day_of_the_week'] == 'Weekend']['delivery_time']

weekday_mean_delivery_time = weekday_delivery_times.mean()
weekend_mean_delivery_time = weekend_delivery_times.mean()

print(f"Mean delivery time on weekdays: {weekday_mean_delivery_time:.2f} minutes")
print(f"Mean delivery time on weekends: {weekend_mean_delivery_time:.2f} minutes")

mean_times = {'Weekday': 28.45, 'Weekend': 22.60}
# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.bar(mean_times.keys(), mean_times.values(), color=['skyblue', 'lightgreen'])
plt.title('Mean Delivery Time: Weekdays vs Weekends')
plt.ylabel('Delivery Time')
plt.xlabel('Day')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Mean delivery time on weekdays: 28.45 minutes
Mean delivery time on weekends: 22.60 minutes

Observations: The average delivery time is 22.60 minutes on weekends and 28.45 minutes on weekdays. This implies that orders are shipped out more quickly on weekends. Weekends may have less traffic or more delivery personnel available, but weekday orders may have delays because of daily congestion or peak hour traffic.¶

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • An exploratory data study of the meal delivery business uncovers numerous interesting insights:

  • The mean time for delivery is longer on weekdays (28.45 minutes) than on weekends (22.60 minutes), indicating that there may be delays caused by traffic or working congestion during the workweek.

  • The preparation and delivery times for 11.31% of all orders exceed 60 minutes, which may have an adverse impact on customer satisfaction.

  • The majority of orders are placed at a few high-performing restaurants, like Shake Shack, indicating significant consumer preference and probably higher service quality.

  • American and Japanese cuisines have the highest order frequency, indicating their popularity among clients.

  • While the majority of consumers offer ratings of 4 or above, there are still 736 unrated orders 'Not given', showing that the feedback collecting method may be improved.

  • The mean order costs roughly 27 dollars, and the company's revenue plan generates a net revenue of about 1,824.10 dollars.

  • Only a few restaurants match the promotional conditions (rating count > 50 and average rating > 4), indicating high promotion eligibility standards.

Recommendations:¶

  • To shorten weekday delivery times, allocate extra staff or improve routes.

  • Highlight well-known restaurants like Shake Shack in advertising campaigns to gain trust among customers.

  • To eliminate unrated orders, offer incentives to consumers who give ratings (for example, discount vouchers or loyalty points).

  • Create unique deals or meal combinations centered on the most popular cuisines, American and Japanese. Also to rise the bars for the following popular restaurants, create discounts on weekdays or weekends and work on food quality and customers marketing.

  • Examine the 11.31% of orders that take more than 60 minutes and collaborate with vendors to enhance speed and efficiency.

  • To enhance overall service quality, provide training or working support to restaurants that have low ratings or long preparation times.
